	<div class="blog-archive-entries-wrapper">
		<div id="unique-entry-id-9" class="blog-entry"><h1 class="blog-entry-title">Kickoff Day <img class="blog-image-smiley" src="../rw_common/plugins/blog/smiley_laugh.png" width="21" height="21" alt="Laugh" border="0" /></h1><div class="blog-entry-date">Saturday, January 09, 2010 </div><div class="blog-entry-body">The 2010 kickoff seemed like it would take for ever to get here. Finally today the kickoff came and this years game is spectacular!<br /><br />This years game Breakaway involves kicking a standard size 5 soccer ball into your alliance goal, with each alliance having two(2) goals along their alliance wall. The goals are have a ramp and a corral system in front and inside. The walls of the goals consist of memory foam to help keep the balls inside the goals. Hanging from the top of each goal, with about 11 inches below them to the ramp, is a chain assembly that acts as a net to help catch the balls as they are flying into the goals. Each ball that is scored into a goal is worth one(1) point each. <br /><br />When a ball is scored into a goal it travels down the corral where then a human player from the alliance receives the ball. Then using the trident the human players use what is called a trident to place the ball onto the ball return. <br /><br />The field is split into three(3) sections with two(2) structures called bumps where in the center are what is called the towers. Each of the two(2) towers have an opening below them called the tunnels. Then bumps are angled platforms that robot have to drive over, you can also drive your robot through the tunnels. In the last 20 seconds of the match robots may then climb on top of what is called thee platform for a 2 point bonus. Robots may also use the tower structure to elevate there robots off the playing surface for the two 2 point bonus. If an elevated robot then lifts another they receive an additional bonus point.<br /><br />You can click the image below for more info on this amazing game Breakaway:<br /><a href="http://www.usfirst.org/roboticsprograms/frc/content.aspx?id=16209" rel="self" title="Breakaway"><img class="imageStyle" alt="FRC2009_Breakaway" src="frc2009_breakaway.jpg" width="480" height="180"/></a><br /><br />~The Robo-Sharks 1612<p class="blog-entry-tags">Tags: <a href="tag-frc.php" title="FRC" rel="tag">FRC</a>, <a href="tag-kickoff.php" title="Kickoff" rel="tag">Kickoff</a>, <a href="tag-meeting.php" title="Meeting" rel="tag">Meeting</a></p></div></div><div id="unique-entry-id-6" class="blog-entry"><h1 class="blog-entry-title">2010 Kickoff</h1><div class="blog-entry-date">Thursday, December 31, 2009 </div><div class="blog-entry-body">The 2010 kickoff is right around the corner, only 9 days left until the live broadcast and webcast. The link for this years webcast was recently posted on the <a href="http://frcdirector.blogspot.com" rel="self">Bills Blog</a>.  <br /><br />The 2010 kickoff live webcast is being presented by nasa on there website. More information for the 2010 FRC Kickoff can be found at the following link:<br /><br /><a href="http://robotics.nasa.gov/" rel="self">http://robotics.nasa.gov/</a><br /><br />Only 9 days left until the 2010 kickoff!<br /><br />~The Robo-Sharks 1612<p class="blog-entry-tags">Tags: <a href="tag-frc.php" title="FRC" rel="tag">FRC</a>, <a href="tag-2010-season.php" title="2010 Season" rel="tag">2010 Season</a>, <a href="tag-kickoff.php" title="Kickoff" rel="tag">Kickoff</a>, <a href="tag-nasa.php" title="Nasa" rel="tag">Nasa</a>, <a href="tag-webcast.php" title="webcast" rel="tag">webcast</a>, <a href="tag-bills-blog.php" title="Bills Blog" rel="tag">Bills Blog</a></p></div></div>
	</div>
	
	 

